 exhaustive research, including archival research and interviews with twelve former Housewives, recovers a history of women’s social justice activism in an era often considered dormant and adds a Canadian dimension to the history of politicized consumerism and of politicized materialism. Radical Housewives reinterprets the view of postwar Canada as economically prosperous and reveals the left’s role in the origins of the food security movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConsumer movementszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCost and standard of livingzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFoodxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHousewivesxPolitical activityzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPrice regulationzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial justicezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aconsumer activism.  aethnicity.  afood security.  aleft history.  amaternalism.  apoliticized consumption.  aprice control.  aradical consumers.  ared-baiting.  aworking-class feminism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751475440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487514754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487514754.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles